<h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold text-white mb-2 leading-tight">Bingo Bonus vs Steady Scoring</h1>
<p class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-8 not-prose">Bingo · Quiz</p>


      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-300 dark:bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>8 min read</span>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-300 mb-8">Every Scrabble player faces this dilemma: do you fish for the 50-point bingo bonus by keeping strong tiles on your rack, or do you maximise every single turn with the best available play? The answer, backed by tournament data, is nuanced — and understanding when to choose each strategy separates intermediate players from experts.</p>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Numbers: What Each Strategy Produces</h2>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">50</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Bingo bonus points</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">2.3</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Avg bingos/game (pros)</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">30-40</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Pts/turn (steady)</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">12-15</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Turns per game</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-gray-300">A steady scorer averaging 35 points per turn over 13 turns totals ~455 points. A bingo-chaser who gets 2 bingos (averaging 75 each with bonus) but only 25 points on other turns: 150 + (11 × 25) = 425. The steady scorer edges it — unless the bingo player can maintain their non-bingo average.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Steady Scoring Wins When</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Board is tight (few open lanes), rack has no bingo potential, opponent is ahead and you need consistent pressure, or you're in the endgame.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
          <p class="text-amber-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">⚡ Bingo Hunting Wins When</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">You're behind by 50+, rack has 5-6 bingo-friendly tiles, board is open with 7+ letter slots available, or early game when tile pool is rich.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">When to Hold Tiles for a Bingo</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">Holding tiles (playing fewer than 7) to set up a bingo costs you turn equity. The question is: does the expected bingo payout exceed what you sacrifice?</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Decision Framework</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Count your bingo-friendly letters (from SATIRE, RETINA, SALINE stems). If you have 5-6, hold.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Check the board: is there a clear 7+ letter lane open? If the board is blocked, take the safe points.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Compare: best play now vs. expected bingo next turn (factoring draw probability). If the gap is < 20 pts, hold.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Never sacrifice more than 1 turn fishing. If you don't bingo on the next draw, play your best word.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-amber-600 dark:text-amber-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-amber-400 pl-4">The Expert Approach: Hybrid Strategy</h2>

      <p class="text-gray-300">Top players don't choose one strategy — they fluidly switch between them. The key insight: rack leave quality determines your next-turn scoring potential. Every play should consider what tiles stay on your rack.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Play the best word that leaves a good rack:</span> A 28-point play leaving RSTLN is better than a 32-point play leaving UUVWC. The 4-point sacrifice pays back 2-3× on the next turn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Don't tunnel-vision on bingos:</span> If your best play scores 40+ points, take it — even if your leave isn't perfect. A bird in hand beats a 30% bingo chance next turn.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Endgame switches to pure points:</span> With fewer than 15 tiles in the bag, bingo fishing becomes unprofitable. Switch to maximising every turn regardless of leave.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

